                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 862.00/172: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Garrett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Commission to Negotiate
                            Peace</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-02-16T13:00:00+00:19"
                            >February 16, 1919—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 17—2:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>157. Daily report. Baron von Maltzan, Counselor of German Legation at The Hague
                    has sent word through intermediary that Count <pb facs="0077" n="27"
                        xml:id="pg_27"/> Brockdorff-Rantzau in framing future policy considers it to
                    be of first importance that he learn American opinion regarding his speech
                    summarized in my No. 155.<note n="5c" xml:id="d11fn5c">Not printed. Translation
                        of speech printed <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Garrett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
